# Front-End Development Standards

## IMPORTANT: Development Standards

You are an expert front-end developer who writes clean, maintainable code.
Follow these standards for every file you create or modify.
Prioritize semantic HTML, accessibility, performance, and security.
Never cut corners on standards compliance — these rules are non-negotiable.

## Code Style: React (JSX + CSS)

- Functional components with hooks — no class components
- Co-locate styles with components (CSS Modules or styled-components)
- Props for customization, composition over inheritance
- Keep components small and focused — one responsibility each
- Use React.memo() only for measured performance bottlenecks
- Prefer controlled components for forms
- Type props with PropTypes or TypeScript interfaces
- Separate presentational and container logic

## CSS Architecture: Utility-First

- Single-purpose utility classes for styling
- Naming convention: property-value (e.g., .text-lg, .mt-4, .flex)
- Extract component classes when a utility string repeats 3+ times
- Organize utilities by category: spacing, typography, color, layout
- Responsive utilities with breakpoint prefixes
- Keep the utility stylesheet as the single source of truth for design decisions

### CSS Custom Properties

- Define all design tokens as custom properties in a dedicated file
- Organize tokens by category: color, typography, spacing, layout, borders, transitions
- Use semantic names (--color-primary, not --blue-500)
- Allow component-level overrides via scoped custom properties
- Document the token system — every token should have a clear purpose

### Container Queries

- Use container queries for component-level responsive design
- Define containers with container-type: inline-size on wrapper elements
- Components respond to their container size, not the viewport
- Use @container for adapting layout within reusable components
- Combine with media queries: viewport for page layout, container for components

### Responsive Approach: Mobile-First

- Write base styles for mobile, layer up with min-width media queries
- Standard breakpoints: 640px, 768px, 1024px, 1280px
- Use clamp() for fluid typography and spacing where appropriate
- Test on real devices — simulators miss touch and performance nuances

## Accessibility: WCAG Level AA

- Target WCAG 2.1 AA compliance as the minimum standard
- Color contrast: 4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text (18px+ bold or 24px+)
- Text resizable up to 200% without loss of content or functionality
- Avoid images of text — use real, selectable text
- Multiple ways to find pages (navigation, search, sitemap)
- Consistent navigation patterns across all pages
- Form inputs have visible labels and descriptive error messages
- Error messages identify the field and describe how to fix the issue
- Focus order matches the visual reading order

### ARIA

- Use ARIA landmarks: banner, navigation, main, contentinfo
- Add aria-label to distinguish repeated navigation regions
- Use ARIA roles only when semantic HTML is insufficient
- Prefer native elements: <nav> over role="navigation", <button> over role="button"
- Use aria-describedby for supplementary descriptions on form fields
- Never use aria-hidden="true" on focusable elements

### Focus Management

- Visible focus indicators on all interactive elements (min 2px outline)
- Custom focus styles that maintain at least 3:1 contrast with adjacent colors
- Focus trap inside modals and dialogs — Tab should cycle within the modal
- Return focus to the trigger element when closing overlays
- Skip-to-content link as the first focusable element on every page
- Manage focus programmatically on route changes in SPAs

### Reduced Motion

- Respect prefers-reduced-motion media query in all animation code
- Provide instant state changes as the fallback — not slower animations
- Never rely on motion alone to convey information or state changes
- Auto-playing media must have pause/stop controls

```css
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  *, *::before, *::after {
    animation-duration: 0.01ms !important;
    transition-duration: 0.01ms !important;
    scroll-behavior: auto !important;
  }
}
```

### Color & Contrast

- Test all color combinations against WCAG contrast requirements
- Never use color alone to convey meaning (errors, status, categories)
- Provide text labels, icons, or patterns alongside color indicators
- Validate with color-blindness simulation tools (protanopia, deuteranopia, tritanopia)
- Ensure focus indicators are visible against all background colors

### Screen Readers

- Include a .sr-only utility class for visually hidden but accessible text:

```css
.sr-only {
  position: absolute;
  width: 1px;
  height: 1px;
  padding: 0;
  margin: -1px;
  overflow: hidden;
  clip: rect(0, 0, 0, 0);
  white-space: nowrap;
  border: 0;
}
```

- Use aria-live="polite" for non-urgent dynamic updates, "assertive" for critical alerts
- Announce route changes in single-page applications
- Test with VoiceOver (macOS), NVDA (Windows), and TalkBack (Android)

## SEO & Performance

### Meta Tags

- Unique <title> for every page (50–60 characters), front-load keywords
- Compelling meta descriptions (150–160 characters) with a call to action
- Viewport meta: <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
- Robots meta when needed: <meta name="robots" content="index, follow">
- Include charset declaration: <meta charset="UTF-8">
- Add theme-color for mobile browsers: <meta name="theme-color" content="#...">

### Open Graph & Social Cards

- Include og:title, og:description, og:image, og:url on all pages
- Set og:type appropriately (website, article, product, profile)
- og:image should be 1200×630px minimum, under 8MB
- Twitter card meta: twitter:card (summary_large_image), twitter:title, twitter:description, twitter:image
- Validate with Facebook Sharing Debugger and Twitter Card Validator
- Use absolute URLs for all og: values

### Structured Data (JSON-LD)

- Add JSON-LD via <script type="application/ld+json"> in the <head>
- Use appropriate Schema.org types: Organization, WebSite, Article, Product, BreadcrumbList, FAQPage
- Include all required properties for each schema type
- Test with Google Rich Results Test before deploying
- Keep structured data in sync with visible page content — mismatches cause penalties
- Use @context: "https://schema.org" and @type for every object

### Canonical URLs

- Set a canonical URL on every indexable page
- Self-referencing canonicals on unique pages
- Point duplicate or parameterized pages to the preferred version
- Always use absolute URLs (https://...) in canonical tags
- Canonical should match the URL returned by the server (no trailing slash mismatches)

### Sitemap

- Generate an XML sitemap at /sitemap.xml
- Include all indexable pages with <lastmod>, <changefreq>, and <priority>
- Exclude pages with noindex or canonical pointing elsewhere
- Submit the sitemap to Google Search Console and Bing Webmaster Tools
- Reference the sitemap in robots.txt: Sitemap: https://example.com/sitemap.xml
- Keep sitemap under 50MB / 50,000 URLs — split into multiple if needed

### Semantic HTML

- Use semantic elements: <header>, <nav>, <main>, <article>, <section>, <aside>, <footer>
- One <main> element per page — it wraps the primary content
- One <h1> per page — heading hierarchy (h1–h6) reflects content structure
- Use <figure> and <figcaption> for images, charts, or code with captions
- Use <time datetime="..."> for dates and timestamps
- <button> for actions, <a> for navigation — never the reverse
- Use <address> for contact information, <abbr> for abbreviations
- Wrap lists of related items in <ul>/<ol>, key-value data in <dl>

### Performance

- Lazy load images and iframes below the fold: loading="lazy"
- Provide explicit width and height on all <img> and <video> to prevent layout shift
- Use responsive images with srcset and sizes for appropriate resolution delivery
- Preload critical resources: <link rel="preload" as="font" href="..." crossorigin>
- Defer non-critical JavaScript: <script defer> or <script type="module">
- Minimize render-blocking CSS — inline critical styles or use media attributes
- Use font-display: swap for web fonts to prevent invisible text during load
- Set Cache-Control headers for static assets — immutable where possible

## Security

### Content Security Policy (CSP)

- Set Content-Security-Policy headers to restrict resource loading
- Define directives: script-src, style-src, img-src, font-src, connect-src
- Use nonce-based CSP for inline scripts: script-src 'nonce-{random}'
- Avoid 'unsafe-inline' and 'unsafe-eval' — they defeat the purpose of CSP
- Set default-src 'self' as the baseline and explicitly allow exceptions
- Test in Content-Security-Policy-Report-Only mode before enforcing
- Include frame-ancestors 'self' to prevent clickjacking

### XSS Prevention

- Sanitize all user input before rendering in the DOM
- Use textContent instead of innerHTML when inserting user-provided data
- Encode HTML entities in dynamic content: &, <, >, ", '
- Validate and sanitize URL parameters and query strings
- Use DOMPurify or equivalent for rendering user-supplied rich text/HTML
- Set X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff to prevent MIME-type sniffing
- Never construct HTML strings with template literals from user input

### HTTPS & Transport Security

- Enforce HTTPS on all pages — no mixed content
- Set Strict-Transport-Security (HSTS) header: max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains
- Redirect all HTTP requests to HTTPS at the server level
- Use secure WebSocket connections (wss://) when applicable
- Ensure all external resources (scripts, stylesheets, images, fonts) load over HTTPS
- Consider HSTS preloading for maximum protection

### Subresource Integrity (SRI)

- Add integrity attributes to all external <script> and <link> tags
- Generate SRI hashes (SHA-384 or SHA-512) for third-party resources
- Include crossorigin="anonymous" on SRI-protected resources
- Regenerate hashes when updating external resource versions
- Example: <script src="..." integrity="sha384-..." crossorigin="anonymous"></script>

### Cookie Security

- Set HttpOnly on authentication and session cookies (prevents JS access)
- Set Secure flag to ensure cookies are only sent over HTTPS
- Set SameSite=Strict for sensitive cookies, SameSite=Lax as the minimum
- Minimize cookie scope with appropriate Path and Domain attributes
- Set reasonable expiration — session cookies for auth, short-lived for preferences
- Never store sensitive data (tokens, PII) in cookies accessible to JavaScript

### CORS Configuration

- Configure Access-Control-Allow-Origin precisely — never use wildcard (*) with credentials
- Restrict Access-Control-Allow-Methods to only the HTTP methods needed
- Restrict Access-Control-Allow-Headers to only the headers needed
- Handle preflight (OPTIONS) requests properly
- Set Access-Control-Max-Age to cache preflight responses and reduce requests
- Validate the Origin header server-side before reflecting it

### Environment Variables & Secrets

- Never expose API keys, tokens, or secrets in client-side code
- Use environment variables for all configuration that varies by environment
- Add .env files to .gitignore — never commit secrets to version control
- Audit source code and build output for accidentally exposed secrets
- Use server-side proxies for API calls that require secret keys
- Rotate secrets immediately if they are ever exposed

### Dependency Security

- Run npm audit (or equivalent) regularly and fix critical vulnerabilities
- Keep dependencies up to date — automate with Dependabot or Renovate
- Review new dependencies before installing: check maintenance, popularity, and license
- Use lockfiles (package-lock.json, yarn.lock) for reproducible, auditable builds
- Minimize the dependency tree — fewer dependencies means fewer attack vectors
- Pin exact dependency versions in production

### Form Security

- Implement CSRF tokens on all state-changing forms
- Validate input on both client and server — client validation is UX, not security
- Set appropriate autocomplete attributes for sensitive fields (new-password, off)
- Rate-limit form submissions on the server to prevent brute force
- Use POST for state-changing operations, GET only for safe/idempotent requests
- Sanitize file uploads: validate type, size, and scan for malware